      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20

I think it is helpful to start with the big picture. Elon Musk is the riche=
st person in the world, and, like many other rich people, he has some unusu=
al and expensive hobbies. One of his hobbies is that he sometimes likes to=
=C2=A0pretend=C2=A0that he will acquire public companies.
  [1]
=C2=A0He seems to find this fun, and why not?=C2=A0When he pretends that he=
=E2=80=99ll buy a public company, it creates a big drama with him at the ce=
nter of it. He gets to boss people around, mobilize legions of bankers and =
lawyers and financing sources and random hangers-on
  [2]
=C2=A0hoping to get the deal done, and then when he gets bored he can tell =
all those people to go home. =E2=80=9CHaha got you,=E2=80=9D he can say, an=
d they can all have a good laugh, or he can anyway.
This is an expensive hobby! When Musk=C2=A0pretended=C2=A0in 2018=C2=A0that=
 he was going to  take Tesla Inc. private, he had to pay the US Securities =
and Exchange Commission=C2=A0a $20 million fine=C2=A0and stop being the cha=
irman of Tesla=E2=80=99s board. You=E2=80=99re not really supposed to go ar=
ound pretending that you will buy a public company; the SEC sometimes consi=
ders that securities fraud. But Musk is very rich and he can easily afford =
to pay $20 million for his little joke. His appetite for pretending to buy =
public companies was, apparently, undiminished.
So this April, Musk announced that he wanted to buy Twitter Inc. Why not? M=
usk seems to get a lot of joy out of using Twitter, and pretending to buy T=
witter is a good way to create=C2=A0drama on Twitter. At the time, I assume=
d that, as with Tesla, he was doing a bit. =E2=80=9COrdinarily,=E2=80=9D  I=
 wrote, =E2=80=9Cif a billionaire chief executive officer of a public compa=
ny offers to buy a company, the odds that he is kidding are quite low. When=
 it=E2=80=99s Elon Musk, the historical odds are, like, 50/50.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0
But he surprised me by quickly=C2=A0lining up financing (paying millions of=
 dollars of fees to banks for commitment letters)=C2=A0and  signing a merge=
r agreement with Twitter. If he=C2=A0was=C2=A0pretending he was going to bu=
y Twitter, those were pretty elaborate lengths to go to? But he frequently =
goes to elaborate (and expensive) lengths for a joke =E2=80=94=C2=A0he sold=
 20,000 branded=C2=A0flamethrowers to make a joke about flamethrowers, and =
also=C2=A0founded=C2=A0Boring Co. to make a joke (???) about tunnels=C2=A0=
=E2=80=94 so who knows. Would he line up billions of dollars of financing a=
nd sign a binding merger agreement with a specific-performance clause and a=
 $1 billion breakup fee as a joke? I mean! Nobody else would! But he might!
In any case, shortly after he signed the deal, the market went down. Twitte=
r=E2=80=99s stock closed at $44.48 on April 12, the day before Musk=C2=A0an=
nounced his offer; he agreed to pay $54.20 per share (420 is a weed joke).=
=C2=A0Since then=C2=A0Twitter has surely lost value: The stock closed at $3=
6.81 on Friday, and other social-media stocks are down significantly since =
April. (Snap Inc. is down about 57% since April 13; even Meta Platforms=C2=
=A0Inc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0Facebook =E2=80=94=C2=A0is down more than 20%.) Mean=
while Tesla Inc. stock, the main source of Musk=E2=80=99s wealth, is down a=
lmost 27% since he announced his offer for Twitter. Twitter is worth less t=
han Musk agreed to pay for it, and Musk is less rich than he was when he ag=
reed to buy it. These are not valid reasons for Musk to get out of the deal=
: The legally binding merger agreement that Musk signed with Twitter does n=
ot allow him to terminate the deal due to changes in the stock market or hi=
s own wealth. But they are reasons that Musk might=C2=A0want=C2=A0to get ou=
t of the deal, even if he wasn=E2=80=99t kidding when he first signed it.
Still, one should remain open to the possibility that he=C2=A0was=C2=A0kidd=
ing when he first signed the deal. =E2=80=9CElon Musk had a well-thought-ou=
t business and financial plan for Twitter that worked in the economic condi=
tions of early April 2022, but conditions have changed and the model no lon=
ger works=E2=80=9D does not strike me as the most plausible description of =
what is going on here. =E2=80=9CElon Musk whimsically thought it might be f=
un to own Twitter, so he signed a merger agreement without taking it too se=
riously and then lost interest a week later=E2=80=9D feels more true to the=
 situation. My first reaction to his proposal to buy Twitter,=C2=A0that it =
was a joke, may have been the correct one. He was just a lot more committed=
 to the bit than I expected.
Anyway:

Elon Musk said he=E2=80=99s terminating his $44 billion agreement to acquir=
e Twitter Inc. and take it private, triggering a legal fight with the compa=
ny.
Twitter has made =E2=80=9Cmisleading representations=E2=80=9D over the numb=
er of spam bots on the social network, and hasn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Ccomplied=
 with its contractual obligations=E2=80=9D to provide information about how=
 to assess how prevalent the bots are, Musk=E2=80=99s representatives said =
Friday in a letter to Twitter as part of a regulatory filing.
Twitter said it will fight back in court.

Here is the letter, signed by Mike Ringler of Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher=
 & Flom LLP, Musk=E2=80=99s lawyer. It =E2=80=A6=C2=A0ehhhhhhh. Ehhhhhhhhhh=
